Phase 0 (storage/Docker) — implemented + verified:
- docker/docker-compose.yml: /app/workspace is now a host bind-mount
  (${BOOKCLAW_WORKSPACE_PATH:-/home/paul/bookclaw-workspace}); dropped the
  bookclaw-workspace named volume. The bookclaw-vault volume stays a separate
  named volume.
- scripts/deploy.sh: writes BOOKCLAW_WORKSPACE_PATH to docker/.env, `mkdir -p`s
  the host dir, and after the build aligns the bind-mount ownership to the
  container's app user (bookclaw/999) via a one-off root container
  (`docker compose run --user 0 --entrypoint chown ...`). Docker doesn't chown a
  host bind-mount the way it auto-owns a named volume, so without this a fresh
  host dir (owned by the deployer) makes the app crash on its first mkdir under
  /app/workspace. Covers the timer path too (build-watch.sh -> deploy.sh;
  bookclaw-build.service runs as User=paul).
- .env.example: document BOOKCLAW_WORKSPACE_PATH.
- gateway/src/init/phase-01-config.ts: stamp workspace/.bookclaw/workspace.json
  (WORKSPACE_SCHEMA_VERSION=1, createdByApp from package.json) on first boot, log
  the version on later boots; fail-soft. No compatibility gate yet (Phase 2).
- tests/smoke-test.sh: Phase 1 asserts the marker is stamped.
- No data migration — the existing workspace was disposable (owner decision
  2026-06-05); the cutover starts on a fresh host dir.

